I can't believe the number of threads we have here complaining about
shipping -- usually how things get broken, this time the cost.

I don't know the size or weight of the converter box, but I can tell you
that I have a standard shipping charge here of $16 for shipping a car radio.
This is based on a cost of $14 for the actual shipment, and $2 for
materials.

Most people consider it fair, but once in awhile someone gripes about the
price.  This is usually the same person who shipped it to me in some crappy
box that was too small, with a couple blocks of styrofoam for packing.  He
doesn't take into account the fact that I had to hit the radio with an air
compressor to blow out all the styrofoam particles (who says it doesn't snow
in Florida?), and then repaired his broken volume control and bent back his
tuning shaft, all without charge.

I once had somebody pack a radio into a USPS &quot;Flat Rate&quot; box, with another
flat rate box folded up inside with the radio, and a note that said &quot;Use
this to return the radio when finished.&quot;  The box was too small and the
radio was damaged.  I made it very clear that I don't do that.

While on the subject, I laugh sometimes at the materials people use to pack
things in.  Sometimes shredded paper, which has very poor cushioning
qualities and adds a lot of weight.  I recently had somebody ship me two
radios -- individually boxed, inside a larger box, and all of it wrapped
with several layers of fabric.  Yes, they were well-packed and the radios
arrived safely, but the dang thing was so heavy that I had to weigh it --
yep!  The boxes and packing were heavier than the two radios!  It would've
been cheaper to pay the UPS Store to pack it!

--
