Basic rules of *buying* on eBay:

1. Never bid more than you are willing to pay for a brown paper bag
containing only miscellaneous parts that may or may not resemble the
picture in the listing.
2. There will very nearly _ALWAYS_ be another one.
3. Always ask about shipping costs.
4. Always instruct the seller how you want it shipped. And through
eBay, not through regular e-mail - get it ON THE RECORD.
5. Pay by either USPS money order or PayPal. Both have legal remedies
in case of fraud that checks and cash do not have.

Basic rules about *selling* on eBay:

1. Be scrupulously honest in the description.
2. Brevity may be the soul of wit, but long, flowery, elaborate (but
honest) descriptions increase traffic on eBay.
3. Many pictures are better than few pictures.
4. Disclose shipping options and costs. eBay provides calculators for
that, even internationally. But restate in the description.
5. *ALWAYS* Ship Insured and with some sort of tracking or delivery
confirmation. You need to be able to prove when an item was shipped
and when it was received.
6. Never ship &quot;surface&quot; internationally. Even to Canada. Make that
clear to any buyer.

It is perfectly acceptable to have &quot;flat-rate&quot; shipping, as long as it
is right-up-front. It is perfectly acceptable to limit shipping
options, as above. And it is perfectly acceptable to have &quot;handling
charges&quot; - for example, if I ship a $50 item insured and with delivery
confirmation, that costs ~$2.00 over the calculated shipping costs via
USPS. So a $2.00 handling fee is not out of line.

I just had a buyer tell me on Sunday that a package had not arrived
(shipped 10/4). When I supplied the insurance and delivery
confirmation, the story changed in a relative instant. I would like to
think it was a genuine 'oops' - but I am glad that I followed my
general habit when dealing with unknown buyers - get confirmation.
$2.00 well spent (by the buyer as it happens).

Well, for me eBay is a way of selling off those items that are *just*
better than Free Monday material, but not quite good enough to wait
long enough for the next Kutztown. And on the buying side, a place to
bottom-fish.

Peter Wieck
Wyncote, PA
